# Agent & LLM Instructions: Principles of Excellent Software (Tauri + Svelte 5 stack)

All development, code generation, and AI assistance for the projects in this workspace must adhere strictly to these rules, architectural specifications, and software engineering principles. These standards ensure premium visual aesthetics, minimal boilerplate, high performance, and robust code maintainability across all applications in the suite.

---

## 1. Core Tech Stack & Standards

Depending on the specific project, the technology stack utilizes the following standards:

### 1.1 Backend & App Framework
*   **Backend**: Rust (Tauri v2) — high-performance system access, low memory footprint, strict security models.
*   **Frontend**: Svelte 5 + TypeScript + Vite — highly reactive, fast compilation, minimal boilerplate.
    *   *Svelte 5 Runes*: Always prefer Svelte 5 runes (`$state`, `$derived`, `$props()`) for new components. If modifying legacy components, maintain the existing Svelte 4 syntax (`export let`, reactive `$: `) or refactor them cleanly to Svelte 5 Runes.

### 1.2 Styling Frameworks by Project
*   **Reaper**: Vanilla CSS only. This project does NOT use TailwindCSS. All styles must be written in scoped `<style>` blocks inside Svelte components or global classes in `src/app.css`.
*   **Textmerger**: Vanilla CSS only (with TailwindCSS legacy in some older elements). Do NOT generate new Tailwind utility classes; write standard CSS classes or scoped `<style>` blocks.
*   **Vesta**: Svelte 5 + Tailwind CSS v4 (`@import "tailwindcss";` in `app.css`). Tailwind utility classes are allowed and encouraged for layout and spacing, but they must utilize the custom theme variables. For complex/premium custom UI patterns (e.g. glassmorphism), write semantic CSS classes in `app.css` or scoped `<style>` blocks.

---

## 2. Design Tokens & CSS Variable Architecture

Do not hardcode hex colors or specific palettes directly in component styles. All styling must be driven by semantic CSS variables defined in each app's `app.css`, allowing the color scheme to be changed dynamically without modifying component logic.

### Canonical Variable Names & Color Schemes by Project

#### Reaper (Vanilla Dark/Light)
```css
:root {
  --bg: #111315;          /* Base app background */
  --surface: #181b1f;     /* Sidebars, panels, primary containers */
  --surface-2: #20242a;   /* Cards, input backgrounds, secondary containers */
  --surface-3: #292f36;   /* Hover highlights, active elements */
  --text: #f2f4f3;         /* Main readable text (high contrast) */
  --muted: #a8b1ad;        /* Secondary/subtitle/placeholder text */
  --border: #343b43;       /* Standard thin borders */
  --accent: #2a9d8f;       /* Focus accent, main actions */
  --accent-strong: #43c2ad; /* Hover state on primary actions */
  --accent-text: #071916;  /* Text color on accent backgrounds */
  --warn: #e9a23b;
  --danger: #e15d64;
  --done: #78c679;
  --shadow: 0 18px 50px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.22);
}
:root[data-theme='light'] {
  --bg: #f5f4ef;
  --surface: #ffffff;
  --surface-2: #ece9e1;
  --surface-3: #ded9cf;
  --text: #20221f;
  --muted: #626b66;
  --border: #d2cdc2;
  --accent: #0f7d72;
  --accent-strong: #0c695f;
  --accent-text: #ffffff;
  --warn: #9a640d;
  --danger: #b53d46;
  --done: #3f7f46;
  --shadow: 0 18px 38px rgba(55, 48, 38, 0.12);
}
```

