### Shared Transitions
Ensure components transition smoothly during theme changes by applying this rule globally:
```css
body, button, input, div, span, nav {
  transition: background-color 0.2s ease, color 0.2s ease, border-color 0.2s ease, box-shadow 0.2s ease;
}
```

---

## 3. UI/UX Visual Harmony Rules (MANDATORY)

Every UI element created or modified must be visually consistent with the rest of the application. This is a premium desktop suite — no raw browser defaults are acceptable.

### 3.1 Input Fields & Textfields
Use `.field` as the container wrapper (handles label + input + helper text layout):
*   Background: `var(--surface-2)`, border: `1px solid var(--border)`, border-radius: `8px` or `12px` depending on project, min-height: `40px`, padding: `0 12px`, color: `var(--text)`.
*   Focus state: transition `border-color 0.15s ease, box-shadow 0.15s ease`. On focus: `border-color: var(--accent); box-shadow: 0 0 0 2px color-mix(in srgb, var(--accent) 24%, transparent);`.
*   Labels above inputs: color `var(--muted)`, font-size `0.88rem`, displayed with `display: inline-flex; align-items: center; gap: 6px;`.

### 3.2 Buttons — Standard & Icon
Standard classes:
*   **`.icon-text`** or **`.btn-primary`**: Action buttons with smooth transitions: `transition: background-color 0.15s ease, border-color 0.15s ease, color 0.15s ease, box-shadow 0.15s ease;`.
*   **`.icon-only`** or **`.icon-btn`**: Square icon buttons, typically `width: 40px; height: 40px; border-radius: 8px; border: 1px solid var(--border); background: var(--surface-2);`.
*   Primary variants: `background: var(--accent); color: var(--accent-text); border-color: var(--accent);`. Hover: `background: var(--accent-strong);`.

### 3.3 Segmented Controls
Use `.segmented` for exclusive multi-option selections (format, mode, auth method).
*   Active button: `color: var(--accent-text); border-color: var(--accent); background: var(--accent);`.
*   Inactive button: `background: var(--surface-2); color: var(--muted);` with hover `background: var(--surface-3); color: var(--text);`.

### 3.4 Toggle Cards & Checkboxes
Never use native `<input type="checkbox">`. Use toggle cards:
*   An element with `role="button"`, `tabindex="0"`, receiving `.active` class when toggled.
*   Active state: `border-color: var(--accent); background: color-mix(in srgb, var(--accent) 15%, var(--surface-2));` with accent icon.
*   Always include keyboard handler: `on:keydown={(e) => { if (e.key === 'Enter' || e.key === ' ') { e.preventDefault(); toggle(); } }}`.

### 3.5 Custom Dropdowns & Selects
Never use raw `<select>` tags for styled select boxes.
*   Dropdown overlay: `position: absolute; z-index: 50; top: calc(100% + 4px); left: 0; right: 0; background: var(--surface-2); border: 1px solid var(--border); border-radius: 8px; box-shadow: var(--shadow); overflow: hidden;`.
*   Detect available screen space: if opened near the bottom, open upward (`bottom: calc(100% + 4px); top: auto;`).
*   Close on `Escape`, backdrop click, or selection.

### 3.6 Range Sliders
*   Pass the current progress as a CSS custom property: `style="--percent: {((value - min) / (max - min) * 100)}%"`.
*   The track fill uses `--percent` to color the active portion: `accent-color: var(--accent);`.

### 3.7 Scrollbars
*   Invisible scrollbars: `scrollbar-width: none;` + `::-webkit-scrollbar { display: none; }`.
*   Thin scrollbars: `scrollbar-width: thin; scrollbar-color: var(--border) transparent;`.
*   Never leave the default thick system scrollbar visible in the app UI.

### 3.8 Modals & Dialogs
*   Backdrop: Glassmorphic backdrop `position: fixed; inset: 0; z-index: 20; background: rgba(0,0,0,0.65); backdrop-filter: blur(8px);` with `fade` Svelte transition.
*   Dialog card: `border-radius: 12px; background: var(--surface-2); border: 1px solid var(--border); box-shadow: var(--shadow);` with `scale` entry transition (`duration: 150, start: 0.96`).
*   **CRITICAL**: The dialog card must stop event propagation (`on:click|stopPropagation` or Svelte equivalent) to prevent backdrop click dismissals from triggering on inner clicks.
*   **Dialog Collision Guard**: Per prevenire crash da doppie aperture simultanee o stuttering visivi, non chiamare mai direttamente `open` o `save` da `@tauri-apps/plugin-dialog`. Importa e usa sempre le funzioni protette `guardedOpen` e `guardedSave` esposte da `src/lib/utils/dialogGuard.ts`.

### 3.9 skeleton Loading States
Instead of simple spinning wheels, use pure CSS shimmering skeletons:
```css
.skeleton {
  background: linear-gradient(90deg, var(--surface-2) 25%, var(--surface-3) 50%, var(--surface-2) 75%);
  background-size: 200% 100%;
  animation: shimmer 1.5s infinite linear;
  border-radius: 4px;
  pointer-events: none;
  user-select: none;
}
@keyframes shimmer {
  0% { background-position: 200% 0; }
  100% { background-position: -200% 0; }
}
```

### 3.10 Beautiful Empty States
When lists, tables, or search views have no data, never display a blank space. Provide a structured empty state wrapper `.empty-state` with an SVG icon, clear header, and a clear "Call to Action" button.

### 3.11 Accessibility & Focus Management
*   **Focus Ring**: Ensure focusable elements (`button`, `a`, `[role="button"]`, `input`) show a clear `:focus-visible` state with `2px` border in `var(--accent)`.
*   **Focus Trapping**: Inside modal dialogs, trap the focus using Svelte keydown hooks, and return it to the trigger element when the dialog closes.

### 3.12 Logical CSS Properties (RTL Support)
Use logical properties to natively support bidirectional layouts (Arabic `ar` language):
*   `margin-left` / `margin-right` $\rightarrow$ `margin-inline-start` / `margin-inline-end`
*   `padding-left` / `padding-right` $\rightarrow$ `padding-inline-start` / `padding-inline-end`
*   `border-left` / `border-right` $\rightarrow$ `border-inline-start` / `border-inline-end`
*   `left` / `right` $\rightarrow$ `inset-inline-start` / `inset-inline-end`

---

## 4. i18n & Localization Standard (15 Languages)

To minimize compiled bundle size, avoid external localization packages. Implement a lightweight reactive derived translation store.

*   **Supported Languages (15)**:
    English (`en`), Italian (`it`), Spanish (`es`), French (`fr`), German (`de`), Portuguese (`pt`), Russian (`ru`), Chinese (`zh`), Japanese (`ja`), Korean (`ko`), Arabic (`ar` - RTL), Polish (`pl`), Dutch (`nl`), Turkish (`tr`), Hindi (`hi`).
*   **Key Merging Strategy**: Import locale JSONs and merge with English as safe key-by-key fallback:
    `ar: { ...en, ...infoEn, ...ar, ...infoAr }`
*   **Translation function `$locale(key)`** or **`$t(key)`**: Derived store that supports flat or nested key access and `{{paramName}}` placeholder replacement.

---

## 5. Keyboard Shortcuts & Keybinds Engine

*   **Input Protection**: Inside the global `handleKeydown` window listener, bypass shortcut logic if the target is an interactive input (`INPUT`, `TEXTAREA`, or `isContentEditable`).
*   **Normalized Combo Detection**: Always parse in fixed sequence: `Ctrl`, `Alt`, `Shift`, `Meta`, then the uppercase key character. `SPACE` represents spacebar:
    `const combo = keys.join("+").toUpperCase();`
*   **Interactive Keybind Recording (`KeybindRecorder.svelte`)**: Active capture window that catches modifiers + normal keys, updates the `shortcuts` store dynamically.

---

## 6. Snackbars & Toast Notification System

*   **durata Standard**: La durata standard obbligatoria per tutte le notifiche toast comuni è impostata a **2.5 secondi (2500ms)** per bilanciare visibilità e immediatezza UX.
*   **Store**: Exposes `snackbar.show(message, variant, duration)` and `snackbar.dismiss(id)`.
*   **Variants**: `success` (green/`var(--done)`), `info` (blue/`var(--accent)`), `warning` (amber/`var(--warn)`), `error` (red/`var(--danger)`).
*   **Micro-Animations**: Use a reactive `#key` block to trigger entry animation (`animate-fade-in-up` / `toastSlideIn`) on every new toast, and a progress bar with custom scaling animation.

---

## 7. Release Notes & Versioning Governance

*   **Propagate Version Bump**: Use corresponding update scripts (e.g. `update_project_info.sh`) to sync the version across PKGBUILD/cargo config/Svelte layouts.
*   **Immediate Change Logging**: Every single modification made to source files by an LLM or AI assistant must be recorded with technical reasons inside `docs/list_of_things_changed.md` immediately.

---

## 8. Bottom-Left GitHub & Attribution Panel Practice

Every client-side app (Tauri/Svelte) must include a standardized, visually premium footer in the bottom-left panel (or within the settings footer if there is no primary sidebar) featuring:
*   **Version Number**: An active link to the repository releases page on GitHub.
*   **License Link**: An active link to the project's license file on GitHub.
*   **Pierpaolo Spadafora Icon**: A round profile avatar (from a local, low-resolution cached file in `assets/avatar.png` or `assets/avatar.png` under `src/assets/` at 64x64 resolution, typically under 10KB) linking directly to his personal website (`https://pierspad.com`).
*   **GitHub Repository Link**: A two-row flex/block link labeled with "GitHub" and "Repo" alongside a standard GitHub SVG icon.

**Design & Shared Practice Guidelines**:
*   **Offline/Low-Res Asset Embedding Rule**: Standardize that profile avatars or background images in attribution components must be cached and stored directly in the repository's assets directory rather than fetched dynamically from external servers.
*   **Lexical HTML & Svelte Block Scoping Boundary**: To prevent Svelte template compilation and parsing bugs, developers must ensure all opened `div` and Svelte block tags (`{#if}`, `{#each}`, etc.) are strictly closed within their correct lexical scope.

---

## 9. Shared Crate / Library Architecture (Optional Heavy Features)

For heavy, optional, or reusable features (such as audio transcription with Whisper, media downloading with yt-dlp, or complex translation engines), do not duplicate logic across different application workspaces. Instead:
*   **Modular Shared Crates**: Extract the common functionality into a highly-cohesive, decoupled, and standalone Rust library crate (e.g. `whisper-common` placed in `lib/whisper-common` of each repository, or as a relative path dependency).
*   **Decoupled & Portable APIs**: Expose generic interfaces using standard callbacks (e.g., progress percentages or stages) and optional cancellation tokens (`CancellationToken`) instead of coupling with Tauri-specific state or handlers.
*   **Optional & Configurable**: Heavy dependencies (like `whisper-rs`, `reqwest/stream`, `hound`) must be encapsulated inside these crates, keeping the main application workspaces clean, light, and easy to build if these features are not utilized or are optional.

---

## 10. Development Speed & Compilation Optimizations (MANDATORY)

To keep iteration times extremely fast and avoid resource locks during parallel development, all developers and AI assistants must follow these build-speed practices:

### 10.1 Fast Linker (mold)
On Linux systems, the Rust toolchain is configured to use the `mold` linker, which is significantly faster than standard GNU `ld` or `gold`.
*   Ensure `.cargo/config.toml` contains target-specific configurations using `mold` as the linker for both `x86_64` and `aarch64` Linux targets.
*   Do not overwrite or disable these configurations unless building for release on non-Linux hosts.

### 10.2 Development Profiles & Optimized Dependencies
Keep the development compilation profiles in `Cargo.toml` optimized:
*   Use `[profile.dev]` with `opt-level = 0`, `debug = 0` (or `1` if debugging is strictly required), and `strip = "debuginfo"` to keep debug symbols out of local builds.
*   Optimize dependencies during development using `[profile.dev.package."*"]` with `opt-level = 1` or higher, which prevents dependencies from running slowly while keeping recompilations fast.

### 10.3 Avoid Port Conflicts in Parallel Development
Each application must use a unique Vite server port for its GUI frontend to allow running them concurrently:
*   **Reaper**: Port `5173` (Tauri devUrl: `http://localhost:5173`, Vite: `5173`)
*   **Textmerger**: Port `5174` (Tauri devUrl: `http://localhost:5174`, Vite: `5174`)
*   **Vesta**: Port `5175` (Tauri devUrl: `http://localhost:5175`, Vite: `5175`)

### 10.4 Skip Compilations with `cargo check`
*   Use `cargo check` instead of `cargo build` when validating code correctness. It runs 2x-3x faster by skipping binary generation.
*   Consider running `cargo watch -c -x check` in the background during active coding.

### 10.5 Sparse Registry & Crate Pruning
*   Always configure `[registries.crates-io]` with `protocol = "sparse"` in `.cargo/config.toml` to download registry indices instantly.
*   Regularly scan for and prune unused dependencies using `cargo machete` or `cargo-shear` to keep the dependency tree lightweight and minimize build times.

